    <Section>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader1}">Is Pluto Really a Planet?</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader2}">by Erin</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleBody}">
            Yes, Pluto really is a planet.
            A planet is a special term applied to the larger members of our solar system that follow two rules.
            Rule 1: a planet must orbit the sun.
            Rule 2: it must be large enough that its own gravity is strong enough to maintain a spherical shape.
            There are certain properties we expect to see in a planet, such as an atmosphere and dynamic, active surfaces at some stage in their history.
            Pluto is far too big to behave anything like the tiny chunks of ice we call comets.
            No, Pluto is not an asteroid.
            Pluto is not a comet, either.
            Scientists say Pluto is a planet.
        </Paragraph>
    </Section>

