        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader1}">Taking a Look in Space</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader2}">by Robbie</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleBody}">
            I want to inform 4th graders about the Hubble Space Telescope.
            I interviewed my dad. 
            He works at NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration).
            The Hubble Space Telescope is a telescope built by NASA that is in orbit around the Earth.
            They put it in orbit because it has a much clearer view of the universe from there.
            The Hubble Space Telescope is about the size of a school bus and was launched April 24, 1990. 
            The telescope has not come down, and is still floating in orbit.
            The telescope takes pictures of planetary nebula, stellar dust, supernovas, and galaxies.
            It can take pictures from long distance.
            For example, it can take images of objects millions of light years from Earth.
            The Hubble Space Telescope travels 276 miles per minute around the Earth.
            As you can see, the Hubble Space Telescope is important for us to understand our Earth and the universe.
        </Paragraph>
    </Section>
    
    <Section>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader1}">Do We Really Need Homework?</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleHeader2}">by Caitlin</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph Style="{StaticResource ParagraphArticleBody}">
            A lot of people in Hammond Elementary School think homework is boring. 
            Ashlee is one of these people. 
            "It is just too easy," she says.
            Kirstan thinks homework rots your brain.
            Other people think it is enjoyable and fun.
            Homework is study you have to do outside of your classroom at home at 3:30 or in the evening.
            My sister Christine thinks homework can be fun or boring or even frustrating.
            She thinks homework is important because you have to study for class so you get a good grade. Christine says, "You have to practice to be good at something."
            She also says that homework teaches you a lot of things like math and social studies.
            Finally, Christine said, "Yes, we really need homework."
        </Paragraph>
    </Section>
    
